Title : John Cairns (politician)
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}
{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}
'''John Cairns''' (1859 - 23 May 1923) was Labour MP for [[Morpeth (UK Parliament constituency)|Morpeth]] from [[1918 United Kingdom general election|the 1918 general election]] until his death, which led to the [[1923 Morpeth by-election]].

Born at [[Choppington]] in [[Northumberland]], Cairns worked as a [[coal miner]] and became active in the [[Northumberland Miners' Association]].  He was elected as the full-time financial secretary of the union, also serving as secretary of the Joint Committee in the Northumberland Coal Trade, and President of the Northumberland Aged Mine Workers' Homes Association.<ref name="stenton">{{cite book |last1=Stenton |first1=Michael |last2=Lees |first2=Stephen |title=Who's Who of British Members of Parliament |volume=III |date=1979 |publisher=Harvester Press |location=Brighton |isbn=0855273259 |page=54}}</ref>

In his spare time, Cairns was active in the [[Primitive Methodist]] movement, and wrote books including ''Money'' and ''Economics of Industry''.<ref name="stenton" />

Cairns was a supporter of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], for which he was elected in [[Morpeth (UK Parliament constituency)|Morpeth]] in 1918.  He served until his death, in 1923.<ref name="stenton" />

